se `\"sauce\"` is likely in the dictionary — even though `\"STEP\"` is a process word that signals the shorter form is correct.\n\nThe motivating case only needs the first arm (`CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`) to work. The second and third arms are pre-emptive generalizations that haven't been validated by failing tests. Unless there is a specific failing case that required them, they should be removed or deferred until such a case appears.\n\nRoot cause: the logic was extended beyond what the described example requires, attempting to future-proof before seeing a concrete need.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 3. Case inconsistency in suffix extraction\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1412-1416`\n\n`suffix` is extracted from `a.text` (original case) via `a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim()`, then normalized with `.toLowerCase()`. But in the per-word arm on line 1416, each word is lowercased again with `w.toLowerCase()`. That is fine for `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. The problem is the `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm)` check on line 1414: `suffixNorm` has already been lowercased and diacritic-stripped, which matches the set correctly.\n\nHowever, `FOOD_DICTIONARY.has(suffixNorm)` on line 1415 operates on the *entire* multi-word suffix as a single key. `FOOD_DICTIONARY` almost certainly does not contain multi-word phrases, so this arm silently never fires for multi-word suffixes. If the intent was \"entire suffix is a known food term\" this is fine but should be documented; if the intent was \"suffix is a food phrase\" it will silently miss.\n\n### 4. Repeated multi-line origin check is not abstracted\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\nThe expression `(a.origin === \"2-line\" || a.origin === \"3-line\")` appears 5 times across the file (lines 1307, 1358, 1410, and in the joins filters). There is no helper like `isMultiLineJoin(candidate)`. This is low friction now but becomes a maintenance issue if a `\"4-line\"` origin is ever added — every branch needs updating independently.\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n### S1. The comment on line 1394 is being strained\n\nThe `DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC` block comment now has a new exception carved directly inside the \"don't change\" region. The comment should be updated to reflect that the rule is \"shorter wins, except for multi-line joins with food-category suffixes.\" The current comment says the pre-filters above handle conflicting cases, which is no longer the full picture.\n\n### S2. The `startsWith` guard on line 1411 is correct but its purpose is implicit\n\n```typescript\naLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")\n```\n\nThis ensures the suffix protection only applies when `b` is a genuine *prefix* of `a` (not a mid-string substring match), which is the right constraint. A brief inline comment stating why `startsWith` is used instead of `includes` — which is used in the outer filter — would clarify the asymmetry for readers.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- Converting the multi-condition original `some()` into an early-return chain (the `if (b === a) return false` / `if (b.text.length >= a.text.length) return false` cascade) is a clear improvement in readability over the old form.\n- The `startsWith` guard correctly narrows the suffix protection to prefix relationships, avoiding spurious matches on mid-string substrings.\n- `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` as a distinct, smaller subset of `SECTION_LABELS` is the right design — the comment on line 170 explaining why it exists is good documentation.\n\n---\n\n## Systemic Pattern\n\nThis is the 6th modification in or around the dedup filter block (the banner says five prior attempts). Each iteration adds another guard with its own vocabulary or structural condition. The block now has: compound-separator protection, multi-line join pre-filters (three separate ones above), position-0 compound protection, and now food-suffix 